#MEM id=writing-skills source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Technical/quinn/skills/superpowers/writing-skills/persuasion-principles.md
M|writing-skills|LLMs respond to the same persuasion principles as humans. Understanding this psychology helps you design more effective skills - not to manipulate, but to ensure critical practices are followed even u
M|writing-skills|**Research foundation:** Meincke et al. (2025) tested 7 persuasion principles with N=28,000 AI conversations. Persuasion techniques more than doubled compliance rates (33% → 72%, p < .001).
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Deference to expertise, credentials, or official sources.
M|writing-skills|**How it works in skills:**
M|writing-skills|- Imperative language: "YOU MUST", "Never", "Always"
M|writing-skills|- Non-negotiable framing: "No exceptions"
M|writing-skills|- Eliminates dec fatigue and rationalization
M|writing-skills|**When to use:**
M|writing-skills|- Discipline-enforcing skills (TDD, verification requirements)
M|writing-skills|- Safety-critical practices
M|writing-skills|- Established best practices
M|writing-skills|**Example:**
M|writing-skills|```markdown
M|writing-skills|✅ Write code before test? Delete it. Start over. No exceptions.
M|writing-skills|❌ Consider writing tests first when feasible.
M|writing-skills|```
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Consistency with prior actions, statements, or public declarations.
M|writing-skills|**How it works in skills:**
M|writing-skills|- Require announcements: "Announce skill usage"
M|writing-skills|- Force explicit choices: "Choose A, B, or C"
M|writing-skills|- Use tracking: TodoWrite for checklists
M|writing-skills|**When to use:**
M|writing-skills|- Ensuring skills are actually followed
M|writing-skills|- Multi-step processes
M|writing-skills|- Accountability mechanisms
M|writing-skills|**Example:**
M|writing-skills|```markdown
M|writing-skills|✅ When you find a skill, you MUST announce: "I'm using [Skill Name]"
M|writing-skills|❌ Consider letting your partner know which skill you're using.
M|writing-skills|```
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Urgency from time limits or limited availability.
M|writing-skills|**How it works in skills:**
M|writing-skills|- Time-bound requirements: "Before proceeding"
M|writing-skills|- Sequential dependencies: "Immediately after X"
M|writing-skills|- Prevents procrastination
M|writing-skills|**When to use:**
M|writing-skills|- Immediate verification requirements
M|writing-skills|- Time-sensitive workflows
M|writing-skills|- Preventing "I'll do it later"
M|writing-skills|**Example:**
M|writing-skills|```markdown
M|writing-skills|✅ After completing a task, IMMEDIATELY request code rv before proceeding.
M|writing-skills|❌ You can rv code when convenient.
M|writing-skills|```
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Conformity to what others do or what's considered normal.
M|writing-skills|**How it works in skills:**
M|writing-skills|- Universal patterns: "Every time", "Always"
M|writing-skills|- Failure modes: "X without Y = failure"
M|writing-skills|- Establishes norms
M|writing-skills|**When to use:**
M|writing-skills|- Documenting universal practices
M|writing-skills|- Warning about common failures
M|writing-skills|- Reinforcing standards
M|writing-skills|**Example:**
M|writing-skills|```markdown
M|writing-skills|✅ Checklists without TodoWrite tracking = steps get skipped. Every time.
M|writing-skills|❌ Some people find TodoWrite helpful for checklists.
M|writing-skills|```
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Shared identity, "we-ness", in-group belonging.
M|writing-skills|**How it works in skills:**
M|writing-skills|- Collaborative language: "our codebase", "we're colleagues"
M|writing-skills|- Shared goals: "we both want quality"
M|writing-skills|**When to use:**
M|writing-skills|- Collaborative workflows
M|writing-skills|- Establishing team culture
M|writing-skills|- Non-hierarchical practices
M|writing-skills|**Example:**
M|writing-skills|```markdown
M|writing-skills|✅ We're colleagues working together. I need your honest tec judgment.
M|writing-skills|❌ You should probably tell me if I'm wrong.
M|writing-skills|```
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Obligation to return benefits received.
M|writing-skills|**How it works:**
M|writing-skills|- Use sparingly - can feel manipulative
M|writing-skills|- Rarely needed in skills
M|writing-skills|**When to avoid:**
M|writing-skills|- Almost always (other principles more effective)
M|writing-skills|**What it is:** Preference for cooperating with those we like.
M|writing-skills|**How it works:**
M|writing-skills|- **DON'T USE for compliance**
M|writing-skills|- Conflicts with honest feedback culture
M|writing-skills|- Creates sycophancy
M|writing-skills|**When to avoid:**
M|writing-skills|- Always for discipline enforcement
M|writing-skills|| Skill Type | Use | Avoid |
M|writing-skills||------------|-----|-------|
M|writing-skills|| Discipline-enforcing | Authority + Commitment + soc Proof | Liking, Reciprocity |
M|writing-skills|| Guidance/technique | Moderate Authority + Unity | Heavy authority |
M|writing-skills|| Collaborative | Unity + Commitment | Authority, Liking |
M|writing-skills|| Reference | Clarity only | All persuasion |
M|writing-skills|**Bright-line rules reduce rationalization:**
M|writing-skills|- "YOU MUST" removes dec fatigue
M|writing-skills|- Absolute language eliminates "is this an exception?" questions
M|writing-skills|- Explicit anti-rationalization counters close specific loopholes
M|writing-skills|**Implementation intentions create automatic behavior:**
M|writing-skills|- Clear triggers + required actions = automatic execution
M|writing-skills|- "When X, do Y" more effective than "generally do Y"
M|writing-skills|- Reduces cognitive load on compliance
M|writing-skills|**LLMs are parahuman:**
M|writing-skills|- Trained on human text containing these patterns
M|writing-skills|- Authority language precedes compliance in training data
M|writing-skills|- Commitment sequences (statement → action) frequently modeled
M|writing-skills|- soc proof patterns (everyone does X) establish norms
M|writing-skills|**Legitimate:**
M|writing-skills|- Ensuring critical practices are followed
M|writing-skills|- Creating effective documentation
M|writing-skills|- Preventing predictable failures
M|writing-skills|**Illegitimate:**
M|writing-skills|- Manipulating for personal gain
M|writing-skills|- Creating false urgency
M|writing-skills|- Guilt-based compliance
M|writing-skills|**The test:** Would this technique serve the user's genuine interests if they fully understood it?
M|writing-skills|**Cialdini, R. B. (2021).** *Influence: The Psychology of Persuasion (New and Expanded).* Harper Business.
M|writing-skills|- Seven principles of persuasion
M|writing-skills|- Empirical foundation for influence research
M|writing-skills|**Meincke, L., Shapiro, D., Duckworth, A. L., Mollick, E., Mollick, L., & Cialdini, R. (2025).** Call Me A Jerk: Persuading AI to Comply with Objectionable Requests. University of Pennsylvania.
M|writing-skills|- Tested 7 principles with N=28,000 LLM conversations
M|writing-skills|- Compliance increased 33% → 72% with persuasion techniques
M|writing-skills|- Authority, commitment, scarcity most effective
M|writing-skills|- Validates parahuman model of LLM behavior
M|writing-skills|When designing a skill, ask:
M|writing-skills|1. **What type is it?** (Discipline vs. guidance vs. reference)
M|writing-skills|2. **What behavior am I trying to change?**
M|writing-skills|3. **Which principle(s) apply?** (Usually authority + commitment for discipline)
M|writing-skills|4. **Am I combining too many?** (Don't use all seven)
M|writing-skills|5. **Is this ethical?** (Serves user's genuine interests?)